Q: Simplest form?

<form>
    <input name="q">
</form>

When you press enter, the URL changes with the input text
?q=text 
is appended to the URL (by default the form submit to itself)

Q: Submit form?
<form>
    <input name='q'>
    <input type='submit'>
</form>
Clicking submit is NOT any different that pressing enter in the first form

Q: How to change where the form submits to?
<form action="http://www.google.com/search">
    <input name='q'>
    <input type='submit'>
</form>
When submit is pressed, the browser goes to google search results
URL: http://www.google.com/search?q=better+flight+search%21                     <-- URL encoding/escaping turned spaces into +, ? into %21

Q: Post request?
Default are GET request (use GET parameters)
<form method="post" action="/testform">
    <input name="q">                                                            <-- type="text" is default
    <input type="submit">
</form>

Q: Password input type?
<form method="post" action="/testform">
    <input name="username">          
    <input type="password" name="p">                                            <-- password is hidden in line edit and when passed to server (but beware of network capture)
    <input type="submit">
</form>
The type=password is only to prevent someone from looking over your shoulder
Note that if the GET method is used, the URL will include the password

Q: What is type checkbox?
<form action="/foo">
    <input type="checkbox" name="q">
    <input type="submit">
</form>
Create checkbox
When checked, q is passwed in the URL and value is 'on' (i.e. /foo?q=on )
When unchecked, q is NOT passed in the URL at all (/foo?)

Q: How to group checkboxes?
Checkboxes cannot be grouped! You are thinking of a radiobutton !
<form action="/foo">
    <input type="checkbox" name="q">
    <input type="checkbox" name="r">
    <input type="checkbox" name="s">
    <input type="submit">
</form>
Here when 2 checkboxes are checked, then .../foo?q=on&r=on

Q: How to group the radio button?
<form action="/foo">
    <input type="radio" name="q">                                           <-- to be grouped, then need to have the same name
    <input type="radio" name="q" value="one">
    <input type="radio" name="q" value="two">
    <input type="submit">
</form>
If first radio is selected q=on, 
the second q=one
the third q=two

Q: How to create labels to radio button?
<form>
    <label> Un
        <input type="radio" name="q">
    </label>
    <label> Deux
        <input type="radio" name="q" value="one">
    </label>A
    [...]
</form>

Q: Dropdowns ?
<form>
    <select name="q">
        <option value="1">the number one</option>                       <-- if selected, ?q=1 is appended to the form action URL
        <option value="2">two</option>
        <option>three</option>                                          <-- by default value is set to the content of the option element
    </select>
    <input type="submit">
</form>

Q: What about validation?
There can be server-side and client-side validation
Server-side validation required because do not trust client ( Required)
client-side validation to make UI more responsive (nice to have)
==> combo box, radio button
But the server should never trust the client !

Q: What is the parameter type in GET requests?
The parameter type from the perspective of the server is string.
So if 1 is passed, you need to day.isdigit() and int(day)

Q: Default value in line edit?
<input type="text" name="q" value="default text">
